    <h3>
    <strong>1. Upper Rogue River – Shady Cove to Dodge Bridge</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing</strong>: Both <strong>summer</strong> (June–Sept) and <strong>winter</strong> (Dec–March) steelhead run here. The early summer "chromers" show up in June, with peak action through October 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Boat ramps at Shady Cove; walk-in access from McGregor Park, TouVelle, Casey, Rogue Elk Park, Dodge Bridge, Takelma Park, and the 234 Bridge
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Approach</strong>: Swing flies, nymph under anglers, drift roe; drift boats excel as reported by local anglers.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Middle Rogue – Grants Pass to Gold Hill</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing</strong>: Steady runs of both summer and winter steelhead, with stronger winter runs around Grants Pass
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Public riverside parks like Matson Park, Valley of the Rogue, Chinook Park, and Coyote Evans Wayside for wading and drift launches
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Techniques</strong>: Nymphing, swinging flies, and drift bounce setups are productive.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Lower Rogue &amp; Rogue Bay (Agness Area)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing</strong>: Giant winter steelhead congregate here late fall through winter 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Remote boat or jet-launch access from Agness; wilderness area so plan for float trips or jetboats
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Why It’s Special</strong>: Fish “chrome hogs” fresh from the ocean—prime trophy potential.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. Applegate River – Cantrall-Buckley &amp; Jackson Camp</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing</strong>: Abundant <strong>winter steelhead</strong>, generally Feb–March .
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: At Cantrall-Buckley Park and Jackson Campground; easier wading in calm, gravel-bottom runs
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Angler Tip</strong>: Less crowded than Rogue—ideal for drift and float presentations.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. Illinois River – Forested Tributary</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing</strong>: Winter steelhead run annually, accessing via rugged spurs 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access</strong>: Public access near Eight Dollar Rd; hands-on trout/steelhead habitat
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Challenge</strong>: Remote and less pressured but riverside access can be tricky.
    </li>
</ul>
