<h2>
    Techniques &amp; Timing
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Summer Steelhead (June–Sept):</strong> Swing spey or two-handed flies; nymph on drifts—target cooler Upper Rogue stretches
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Winter Steelhead (Dec–Mar):</strong> Heavier drift nymphs, roe, worms; better flows make mid‑lower Rogue and Applegate hot spots .
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boat vs Wade</strong>: Boats cover more water, but wading remains excellent in accessible tailouts—shore anglers have landed fish too .
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Conservation &amp; Local Tips
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        Stick to <strong>hatchery-marked fish only</strong> for harvest; wild steelhead must be released.
    </li>
    <li>
        Use <strong>barbless hooks</strong>, handle fish gently, and minimize air exposure.
    </li>
    <li>
        Rangers encourage staying off redds (gravel nests) during spawning to protect habitat.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Summary: Best Steelhead Spots near Medford
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Upper Rogue (Shady Cove to Dodge Bridge)</strong> – Summer &amp; winter runs; mix of boat and wade.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Middle Rogue (Grants Pass to Gold Hill)</strong> – Winter steelhead in calmer stretches.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Lower Rogue (Agness/Rogue Bay)</strong> – Trophy winter chrome steelhead.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Applegate River</strong> – Quiet, accessible runs ideal for drift anglers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Illinois River</strong> – Remote but rewarding winter steelhead chance.
    </li>
</ol>

